A new science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to ponder the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In light of the major challenges, it is believed that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved mysteries of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), which require enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World to explore. Secondly, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solutions must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, many believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny this?
The models of today do indeed work.
However, an increasing group of scientists points out phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
These problems do arise more frequently, but they are also cleverly circumvented because the science needed to explain these problems simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is relatively well secured.
Physics, at least the part we encounter as ordinary people, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – there may still be a few things in our bodies that we do not understand, but it can be assumed that the basic mechanisms of cell and molecule interaction are known.
Moreover, there are the new social sciences that focus on people and societies.
In each of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are firmly established and largely uncontested.
Each discipline has its own language and mechanisms.
Rarely is a scientist an expert in more than one field because these worlds and languages are so different.
This means we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the integration of several disciplines.
For example, think of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs on the basis of physics. The information transmitted is conveyed due to the laws of electricity.
Moreover, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information.
In the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: Here, information exchange takes place via language, symbols, and ideas.
At each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes at each level.
However, information is also exchanged between these individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To address this gap, some scientists have tried to redefine the toolkit for explaining processes within one level, then applying it to another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works well, but the fundamental problem is not solved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between individual levels, and how is it transmitted?
Now almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The interdisciplinary group of scientists who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and disciplines and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
Besides scientists from relevant fields, artists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," where scientific foundations are adapted and extended from one level to another.
Others, however, believe a completely new approach is necessary.
In your opinion, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents, and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches may emerge through scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Total freedom of thought is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that take place under the banner of "science," like their counterparts in the business world, have developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries must build similar resources as industrial countries. This could, however, stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas originate from laboratories and research centers that have no connection to the large institutions.
The most thoughtful approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where computer capacities were lacking at all corners.
The most brilliant and truly world-shaking insights in physics over the last decades did not come as expected from the known innovation hubs, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that has led cognitive scientists to important discoveries.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") today come from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unexpected start of an attempt to redefine the universe in this manner.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations need to be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be included in this group to identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, if one wishes.

